I am upgrading the build platform on my Prusa and liked the thumbwheels from HBP Quick Leveler Redux, but I needed some to fit M4 nuts.  So I decided to write a parametric OpenSCAD script to make thumbwheels of any size.  The included stl is for an M4 nut.

If you need M4 thumbwheels, use the included stl and make as many as you need using multiply in skeinforge.  If you need a different size, download the .scad file and have fun.  I included lots of comments to hopefully make it easy.

comments.text: Just had a look at your script and your method for creating captive nuts is interesting but I wanted to let you know there is an easier way. If you create a cylinder with 6 facets and a radius of the nuts width across the flats divided by the square root of 3 you will have a hexagon the correct size! So in openscad this might look like the following:
comments.author: bwevans

comments.text: I like your suggestion and tried something similar after I wrote this little script.  Interestingly enough, I did not invent the hexagon method found in my script: I copied it out of the Prusa Mendel OpenSCAD source.  =-O

description.text:
Please watch this video for more information: https://youtu.be/16rib1vtlqc This is the entire first level of Super Mario Bros for the NES. I modeled it in Tinkercad at a scale of 1 pixel = 1mm. I printed them at 0.3mm layer height with 10% infill on my Robo 3D R1. Then my wife painted them by spraying primer on them, airbrushing the base coat, and then painting the details on with simple acrylic paint. I included the basic tiles so you can pretty much create any level you want that uses these tiles. But I've grouped the tiles for easy printing of World 1-1 specifically. And if you want to print that level, the quantities are listed below. Quantities:

description.text: This is just a rework of the predecessor.  I had support printing issues with the original design so I split it up to be glued together later.

I redid the same customizer the previous thing did, but with no hole in it.
I then hacked up some OpenSCAD just to create the little peg/hole on each part I then subtracted out the screw hole locally using MeshMixer and a bolt of the correct size (bolt2.stl). Now, depending on how your printer prints, you may need to adjust the hole.
If you need to, edit bolt2.stl and scale it in the X/Y direction ONLY so that the threads remain the correct height. Then, subtract that bolt out of the "handle part no hole.stl" file. I'd recommend trying a small cylinder a few times to get things dialed in before wasting your time printing the whole tap handle.

title: TRIPLE the strength of your brackets!

description.text: Another strength related test similar to Formed bracket done earlier. I printed a punch and die with the dart built in. Took just over 2hrs.  Then using Solidworks designed my bracket as a sheet metal part and flattened the blank. clamped all three together and dipped in boiling water to the die set, about 10 seconds. Immediately rinse in cold water and release clamp. Once again this design of brackets can be applied in more strenuous applications that a 3D printed bracket may not have been chose for before. Added bonus, I can pump these brackets out at just under 10 minutes each complete.  If you were to make this part from nylon and use the boiling method as well, it will in turn strengthen the print.  Ive attache an STL for the flat version and formed. I challenge you to make the part both ways and let me know your findings!  Keep an eye out for more things from me to tackle the weak points of printed parts. Thank You

title: 3-way 1" Aluminum Square Tube Connector (For Quick Frame-style tubes)

description.text:
If you're building something out of 1" square aluminum tube, you can use this connector to put the extrusions together. The hexagon stub is there to print without overhangs, and doubles as a cool looking bumper. Places you can buy 1" square aluminum tubes that fit onto this connector: -80 / 20
-Brunner Enterprises
-EZ Tube I used these to make a printer enclosure for my TAZ 5. Photos of the full build here:
http://imgur.com/a/O3H5r

title: The M577 Armored Personnel Carrier (APC) from Aliens

description.text: Had Aliens on in the background and really wanted to see a printable model of this awesome prop happen. The wheels print captured and spin, the turrets snap on the top and should spin with some elbow grease. Happy printing.

MakerBot

MakerBot Replicator (5th Generation)

Doesn't Matter

title: Toranado Robo3d R1+ Carrier and Fan

description.text: This is an X carriage for the Robo 3dR1+ allowing it to use the Toranado Extruder. You can find this wonderful extruder upgrade at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1246951 You will not be able to use the TPGe_40mmfanduct with this carriage. I have included a fan that will attach to the back the carriage to supply cooling for the print. There have been a few questions on how to config this for the Robo 3d R1+. First, the wires for the stepper motor match the colors for the NEMA 17 motor it is replacing. You should be fine there. Next, we need to address the firmware. You should have a copy of the firmware since you changed the setting for the installation of the E3d V6 hot end. If you do not, go to the robo site under support and download the firmware named "Lead screw upgrade". In the firmware you need to change the following: #define INVERT_E0_DIR true #define DEFAULT_AXIS_STEPS_PER_UNIT {80,80,800,420} For the extrusion number, I calibrated based on the wonderful instructions at http://reprap.org/wiki/Triffid_Hunter's_Calibration_Guide . If the print isn't working out just run through the calibration yourself and see what you get. Please comment with any changes you needed to make to your machine if they differ from what I have posted.

Robo 3D

Doesn't Matter

Yes

.2

20%

Notes: I printed the fan in ABS to allow flexibility. I printed the carriage in PLA for the extra rigidity.

Hi Spidermatt,
The adjustment is on the stepper motor controller, attached to the RAMPS 1.4 boards, which is mounted under the Robo 3D R1+. You adjust the small POT to change the voltage needed. Youtube has several videos on changing stepper motor voltage - much better than I can explain in text here. If you need more help, comment again and I can try to help you. Thanks!

author: shivinteger

description.text:
loved the original, saw the remix....but was a bit un-tidy...so I made this....
seems to be just as loud, and makes a sound with slightly less effort...;)
worth a print if you want a slightly smaller version....thx Jzisa for the V29!!

comments.text:
I have printed several of these and cannot get the inside to be clean enough to whistle. I even paused it immediately before the top layer was applied and cleaned out the interior......No go still. What extraction/fill etc are you using?????
btw, my dog hears this thing very well. As soon as I blow it she perks and up and eventually starts howling......poor thing.
comments.author: Readynerd

comments.text: it was printed on my Zortrax M200 with no support, all other details were set by the printer its self....its got a quite high tolerance so some times stuff does not print on all printers... but see if you can turn off the support....also see if you can print the original version, that may print better for you...
comments.author: Readynerd

comments.text: I got it to print but it doesn't produce a whistle, poor layer adhesión on the inside?
comments.author: NikKapur

comments.text: I think your file is broken. It does not slice correctly with Slic3r. Please fix. Its a good design
comments.author: BadPractice

comments.text: Which kind of filament do you have used? It looks a little bit metallic
comments.author: Dr_Peacock

comments.text: maybe the light....its ABS......or Z-ABS (zortrax brand)
comments.author: Dr_Peacock

comments.text:
Awsome!
I printed it on a witbox solid
It is slightly less loud then the origanl (just enough to not make your ears ring) and also works when you blow in gently.
I love it!
comments.author: BadPractice

comments.text: great news, the blow gently sound, works quite well, and i am pretty happy with that....as this is not present on unit, before I re-mixed.
comments.author: BadPractice

remixed_from.title: Normal distribution sliced to show "68-95-99.7 Rule"

description.text:
This is the normal distribution, made with three channeled lines; one to mark the mean, and two to mark what is approximately half way out (s=1.5) on it. This does not mean that 50% of the data would fall between these two lines (quite a bit more, actually; about 86%).
This is meant to operate as a physical model for assisting the visually impaired with understanding common statistical problems, such as any queston that asks for what percentage falls between two given z scores. The being able to physically feel the lines gives a better understanding of what the question is asking, even if the lines are not in accurate places.
Printed in HIPS on a Lulzbot TAZ (5, I think). Bed Temp: 110 C, Extruder: 240 C, Settings were on Quick Print.

Unsure

Notes: In Cura, I selected the standard brim from the simple printing menu, and it worked fine with printing this "laying down" as it was.

Remove Brim I didn't get a picture, because this was the first time I'd printed with brim and was excited to be able to peel it off. But, when printed with a brim, there is a bit of brim that will be left over on the channels through the underside of the model. I used forceps (tweezers) to peel this brim away.

All Steps Remixed ayoung's "Normal distribution sliced to show "68-95-99.7 Rule"" model by removing the numbers and splitting the pieces before sticking them all together.
I then took this piece and used it to cut out a section from a (roughly) circumscribed rectangular prism. I then used this cut out on another rectangular prism of the same size to get back to a (now much smoother) curve piece.
Then, I made a small rectangular prism (the dimensions of which I forget) and copied it six times, then used it to slice the channels in the model for the markers (cut one body using another).

Or you so desperatly need to tight that loose screw and you can't seem to found your bit holder, print one up ^^ Even better, you need a tool that doesn't exist, just make it using the guidelines listed below and your creation will be compatible with every OMT² tooolheads/handles AND every standard bit holders you can come upon...

  • Whiteboard Precision Eraser : http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1363296

• The Original OMT² handles : http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1359158
  • The Double Sided handles : http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1363379
  • The Hex Male-Female Extensions : http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1385071

• Storage - Racks & boxes : http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1370801
  • Precision Tests for bit holders : http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1381733

For your tool bit to be compatible with 1/4" Hex bit holders and/or OMT² handles, it needs to follow this guidelines :
  • It must be a 6 sided polygon
    • All dimensions are given "flat to flat" (Circumbscribed diameter) Male (Plugs for tool bits)
    heigth is always 5.5mm for tool bits

    Tight : 1/4" (6.35mm) => radius : 3.175mm
    Basic : 6.25mm => radius : 3.125mm
    Loose : 6.15mm => radius : 3.075mm

    Female (Sockets for handles)
    depth is always 6mm for sockets

    One size only : 6.70mm => radius : 3.35mm

What needs to be done
  • Redo all the tools and bits in parametric (openSCAD)
  • Create crazy/useless/funny tool bits

This project is the evolution of the (now discontinued) "Open Multi Tool" project. The main difference between the 2, is the ability to use all OMT² toolheads and handles with any 1/4" (6.35mm) Hex bits and handles that you probably have lying around and/or that you can found in any hardware shop around the world.

This is a simple earbud holder I designed using SolidWorks. The inspiration was those plastic holders on a sliced bread bag. The ends of the part are similar to that shape to keep the wires in place. This holder is great to use if you want a low profile holder for your earbuds as it is very flat so it can fit in your pocket without create much of a bulge. The notch on one of the end was meant to hook the end of the earbuds so that that part is kept in place and making wrapping the wires around easier. The center cut outs were mainly meant to reduce amount of filament used and time printing but can also be used to loop the earbud around the wires if it doesn't make it all the way to one end. I used the cord length from my own earbuds so that it would make it all the way to one end. I use this pair if anyone is curious. http://amzn.to/1SBArjg

description.text: A 1:100 scale concept model for a house in Western Australia. The relatively flat, narrow site and the local council interpretation of planning laws conspired to create the interesting 3rd floor mansard roof form. The project was modeled in Archicad, where it was broken into small enough parts to fit the build plate. This also allows for the client to take apart the model and get a better idea of the spaces. The parts were then cleaned with Netfabb and printed on the Makerbot Replicator 2. Though the model pieces should fit on our build plate at 1:100 scale we had numerous issues with the printer at this scale due possibly to the proximity to the edge of the build plate. This issue seemed to be resolved by reducing the scale ever so slightly down to nominally 1:110. The small walls that are 14cm in length on many of the models were there for scaling purposes and can be discarded after printing. A little bit of glue and post production work was required for items like louvres and balustrades, but overall this is probably our most successful model to date. Model photographs by photographer extraordinaire Tim Lofthouse - http://www.lofthouse.com.au/1.html

comments.text: I took a 2'x2'x3/4" piece of MDF. Routed out the slots using a 2 straight flute, 1/4 inch router bit using the Mostly Printed CNC with a Dewalt DW660. I followed that up with a 1/4" shank T-Slot bit using my Bosch fixed base router. Turned out pretty nice.

title: Phone holder for vehicles with a cassette tape

description.text:
I made this to hold my iPhone 5 for my Audi A4 with a cassette tape deck. It fits perfectly in the slot. 
I made two. Once with a recess to apply a rubber tape so the phone doesn't slide off and one without. See the pictures. 
Made and printed in ABS. Let me know if you would like one with modified dimensions for your phone and case.

Any

author: alexsuares

description.text:
Just a quick couple of tools to help those of us with less than Josh Bixlers' skills at carving foam board.
Quick print, carefully insert a single edge razor blade, and you are good to go.  Align the edge of the "John's Wing Thing" with the edge of the foam board you are wanting to cut, and firmly pull it along the edge.
Works a treat for me!
60 and 45 degree versions included, and these are sized to cut 5mm foam board and leave the seam intact, so you can cut single and double edges.

Printer:

A1

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Not Critical

Infill:

40%

Notes: Prints upright, needs a decently calibrated printer as you are literally printing a slot a razor blades width.

I needed a replacement drawer for my small parts organizer and looked around thingiverse for a starting point.  I liked the drawers attached to the Small Parts Cabinet thing so I ginned up a parametric OpenSCAD script to create something similar.  Almost everything about the script is adjustable.  The included stl is a standard drawer with three compartments made to fit a store-bought organizer.

If you need a standard three compartment drawer, download the stl, skein, and print.  Skein with 0 extra shells and 0.0 infill density for a nice sturdy and clean box.  If you need a different size or a different number of compartments, download the scad file and tweak to your heart's content.

comments.text:
Worked great, very nice parametric model! Here are the measurements I used to replace/replicate a drawer for a metal Akro-Mills organizer (Drawer said: 20-445 Acro-Mills Inc Akron Ohio USA PAT. 2985333 84-8)
corner_r = 2; // Radius of the box corners. Set = 0 for square corners. (aesthetic choice)
width = 55.5; // Width of outer box dimension (x-axis) IMPORTANT
depth = 149; // Depth of outer box dimension (y-axis) IMPORTANT
height = 31.5; // Height of outer box dimension (z-axis) IMPORTANT
handle_h = 25; // Height of handle (Aesthetic choice)
handle_d = 10; // Depth of handle (how far does it stick out) (Aesthetic Choice)
handle_w = 10; // Width of the front of the handle (grip flange) (Aesthetic Choice)
handle_r = 3; // Radius of handle fillets (Aesthetic Choice)

title: Phone amplifier using parabolic focal point

description.text:
This is a design I made to "amplify" the sound coming from your phone's bottom speaker. In reality this design focuses the sound coming from the phone by placing the speaker port right at the focal point of a very specific parabolic curve. Think of it like a flashlight. But with sound. You will be impressed with how much this concentrates the sound in one direction!
The design also incorporates a channel to allow you to charge your phone while in use. How convenient! 
Right now I've modeled these for some various sizes of iPhones and cases. But you can message me and I will modify my models for your own phone/case combination. 
Print as if a bathtub with support material. It will have to be cut out later.

Printer:

XYZ Da Vinci

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

100 for best

Infill:

Any

I printed at a .1 mm with supports and 15% infill.

description.text:
Simple tool to help keep lifters in the case half while closing it up. 
Print at least 3 shells and 15% fill.
You will need to wrap a couple layers of electrical tape around the ends to keep the lifters on there snug.

I use this to water my plants. Therfore I needed a cheap and small valve. The valve I used is normally used to controll the airflow in fish tanks and costs about 1 Euro. A typical example on Amazon for the valve would be this ohne
http://www.amazon.de/dp/B001PNUEA2

Shorten the valve lever and the Servoarm to fit within the coupling.
Put all together and close the houseing.
There should be no glue needed.

Bolt on enclosure for the Geeetech G2S. Stepper motor assembly needs to be removed in order for the bottom plates to be installed, that just bolt on using the vertical smooth rod screws. need to print
3x bottom plates (one for each corner)
3x top plates
12x posts (4 for each corner)
2x bottom lips (to join the bottom plates together (one isnt required for the front
1x top tray (fan housing for exhaust port on the top, and doubles as a handy storage tray) parts required
3mm Acrylic or PVC plate plates just slide in from the top creating a sealed chamber. Note this is a work in progress, more updates and pictures to come note these need to be rotated 90 degrees (on X axis) and printed without any supports or rafts

Printer:

Geeetech G2S

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

0.2mm

15%

title: Magnetic Glass Print Bed Holder Tabs

description.text:
Magnetic Mounting Tabs for Glass Printbed. Goodbye clips!
Steel balls make single-point contact on glass for consistent positioning everytime. STL file included is for the Kossel Mini:
15mm aluminum extrusion
13mm dia x 2.5mm x 6 neodymium magnets
1/4 inch steel balls x 3
170mm diameter sheet glass Customize according to your own machine using the included SCAD file. It is essential that only the steel balls should touch the bottom of the glass plate when mounted. Glue the balls and tab magnets first. Install the tabs on your machine.
The balls should be higher than the two magnets (plus a small gap) stuck to each other. To make sure there is a thin gap between magnets, place a shim (2-3 sheets of paper) cut to shape to fit on top of the tab magnet. This ensures there will be a gap between the two magnets. Stick the second magnet on top of the tab magnet, sandwiching the shim.
Try placing the glass on this setup. The glass should be slightly higher than the balls, barely touching them. If not, add more shims. Then you can glue the glass on top of the second set of magnets. When the glue dries and you remove the shims, only the balls should be touching the bottom of the glass plate.

author: shadowpulse3547

description.text: This is a remix of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:977666 a little simpler look.

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

This is a sharps bin that was conceived to aid in developing nations around the world. Bloodborne pathogens are often spread through shared and "recycled" needles. This design would help to reduce the spread of disease by providing an inexpensive, reproducible receptacle for medical facilities to dispose of used needles. The design utilizes a two piece construction - the main component being the bin, the second being an insert to help prevent the extraction of used needles from the bin. The reason for the insert is to allow for the "fingers" to be printed in a direction conducive to flexing. Other design features restrict the orientation in which the bin can be printed, and if printed as a single unit, the "fingers" would be printed as tiny rings. The many layers of rings would cause the "fingers" be brittle and prone to breaking from the insertion of needles.
Another design feature is a sloped bottom within the container to maximize the number of needles that could fit inside. With a conventional "box" shape, needles have the potential to cross and stack irregularly. The sloped bottom allows needles to settle in a more organized fashion, reducing wasted space.
The top of the bin is sloped in order to facilitate hassle free printing of the overhang. The slope of the top was designed to be the minimum angle required to maintain printability while maximizing volume.

• Print both files using support material only on sharps_bin_insert.stl
  • Remove support material from sharps_bin_insert.stl
  • Assemble the two pieces by snapping the insert into the hole of the container

Emax RS2205 propeller wrench, to hold your motor while you are screwing / unscrewing the prop on it. Available on Shapeways.

comments.text: Printed and works very well. Nice job !
comments.author: gebeclair

comments.text: I printed this for my Emax MT2204 II Cooling motors after looking at pics of the 2 motors side by side online. The wrench is nice but it doesn't fit my motors. The spacing is slightly bigger than the RS2205 motor bells.
comments.author: KTMRider

comments.text:
Good to know.
Do you have the spacing of the vent cuttings for the MT2204?
So I can upload a version of this tool for these motors.
comments.author: KTMRider

comments.text: The spokes are 2.22mm thick. The spaces between the spokes are 7.1mm at the outer most part of the bell and taper into 4.9mm. I measured different places on all 4 motors and got the same measurements.
comments.author: ZeblodS

Creations for the Xiaomi Yi camera to go with my Quadcopter creations Changelog 02-FEB-2016 Case_Yi_v5_2_0_no_block : Version without the slide block 02-NOV-2016 Case_Yi_v4_1_1 : Fixed the slide-block (1mm too long) 27-OCT-2016 Yi_Battery_case_v_1_0 : For protection of the extra Yi batts :) print 2 to get a inclosure 23-OCT-2016 Case_Yi_v4_1_0 : Thicker walls 12-JUN-2016 Case_Yi_v4_0_1 : Removed all STL files and added this version. Fits with a lens protector, but does not necessarily need it. 07-MAY-2016 Case_Yi_v3_6_0 : New version designed in SolidWorks. Fits perfect, and should be used together with a lens protector like this http://www.gearbest.com/action-cameras-sport-dv-accessories/pp_184752.html 14-MAR-2016 XYI_Case_v2_0 : Merged version, and small adjustments to the lens, wi-fi and on/off button hole. Should be printed with support (touching build plate). 01-MAR-2016 XYI_Lens_Protec_v1_0 : A lens protector, not pretty, but works. Should be super glued to the case and fastened by the velcro strap when mounted. XYI_Case_v1_0 : First iteration of the Xiaomi case with a prevent-slide-block. Use with http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1296746 or http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1070404

I liked the iPhone 4 Combo Tripod and Stand thing but wasn't crazy about it's printability.  So I made something similar that can be printed without support on just about anything.  My iPhone4 fits slightly loose in the holder, so I put a rubber band around the phone and mount to hold it securely.

Download, skein, and print.  You will have to run a 1/4-20 tap through the hole before you can screw it onto a tripod.  I added the tap as a part because thingiverse does not have tap/die as a tool.
Update 04-Jan-2012: Added the OpenSCAD file.  It was written quick, dirty, and not parametric.

author: Smoozi_ldz

title: Samsung Galaxy Note 10.1 Stand
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
I made this stand for my Samsung Galaxy Note 10.1 for I did not find any made like I wanted it to be. I also wanted it small so I could easy take it with me.
its made to fit on the note on the sides. After it has been fasten the note is in a better angle to write on, when it lay on a flat surface.
Its very secure and you do not bother that it will fall apart, like many other stand. Also if you glue some rubber or something on the bottom of the parts you can remove any slipping between the stand and your flat surface. When you print it out you can do it either flat to the build plate and do not need any support, but the side on the parts will be the surface you have from your printer.
If you like it look better, like I do, you can stand it up and use support. If you use makerware it will only make the support on 2 spots and its very easy to remove. The side will be that resolution you have on your printer. I printed my on 0.2mm and its looks very good and it took around 3 hours. But I will print one other with 0.1mm or better and in black or a some good looking color.
I did this with autodesk 123D Design, instead for inventor. Just for it was so simple thing.

title: Guitar Amp Footswitch / Effect pedal box

description.text:
When I started to play guitar I always had to switch channels and turn effects on/off manually. As you can imagine, that was annoying and it definitely is not cool! ;) My practice amp is an Roland Cube 30x which can change channels from clean to lead and turn effects on and off through a footswitch that was not included when I bought it second hand. When I did want one I quickly thought of printing my own. As you can see in the images, it glows in the dark due to the fact that I had some luminous filament laying around and I thought it would be handy to still be able to see it in the dark. It actually works quite well. I left the bottom open for now, you might want a cover plate on it, but I didn’t feel the need for it as of now.
All you need is:
2 footswitches
1 stereo jack socket
1 stereo jack cable of a length that suits your needs
finally some wire and a soldering iron The guitar stand in the pictures can be found on my profile as well. This was very handy for tuning and maintaining my guitar without damaging the headstock. Good luck printing it, let me know what you think in the comments and feel free to ask questions.

Printer:

XYZ Da Vinci 1.0A

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2-0.3

Infill:

60%

Notes: These are roughly the settings I used, I did use support material to support the hollow section on the bottom, because printing it face down didn't give a good result.

When I started to play guitar I wanted the best value for money guitar I could get. This meant searching for a second hand guitar. With second hand guitars you probably have to do some adjustments or maintenance to the guitar. Letting a store do it is expensive and that negates the effect of buying cheap in the first place. So together with the internet (mainly YouTube) I learned myself how to tune, maintain and setup guitars. One of the things I think that is most important is, to have a support for the neck so the headstock doesn’t get damaged on your workbench. Since I have a 3d printer I thought, why not make one. This design was created in less than 5 minutes and it actually works quite well. For some further protection I use a large towel on top of the bench with this underneath so the body and neck do not get scratched from contact with the bench or this support. The support is slightly slanted because thin guitars (i.e. electric guitars) will most likely sit at an angle. 
As you can see, the print I did isn’t the cleanest, but since I use a towel on top it is not a big issue. I did not use support material, but you can use it to make it a little stronger in the middle. Mine has some “webbing” on the bottom due to the lack of support. Not a big deal, but not the nicest look. 
The guitar amp footswitch / effects pedal box in the pictures can be found on my profile as well. 
Good luck printing it, let me know what you think in the comments and feel free to ask questions.

25%

I did not use support material, but you can use it to make it a little stronger in the middle. Mine has some “webbing” on the bottom due to the lack of support. Not a big deal, but not the nicest look. Resolution is also not that important. I would advice using the fastest speed/setting you have. Good luck printing it, let me know what you think in the comments and feel free to ask questions.

description.text:
Hello,
This is GP-30 (Russian grenade launcher) Handgrip for airsoft.

Well we've seen several models of Capaldi's version of the Sonic and so we thought we'd release our basic version for free on here.
This is as accurate as possible. Designed by Chris Thompson of CT Designs using dimensions taken from an official version of the prop and painted by us at It's An Ashton. Its a simple static version great for use for getting pics taken and we've had many happy customers worldwide.
Enjoy

author: DamianGto

description.text: M5 Mutter auf Schlüsselweite 10mm

This is a luxury yacht that I modelled and thought I'd share with you all. The files are already positioned in the best way to get a good print using an FDM printer. Modelled at 1:40 scale, I scaled down the model by 50% and it took about 14 hours to print on 0.06 resolution on the Ultimaker 2. No clean up done on my boat print apart from removing supports and gluing together, but it prints very clean. If you weight the keel the model will actually float. Check out my portfolio for more work: http://imacke.com Enjoy!

Recently getting into quadcopters I was sick of my lock nuts and base getting scratched up from bouncing off the concrete and figured these would be less drag in the grass. I have an extremely strong double sided (low profile) foam tape that holds these skids to the base no problem. The clearance holes are big enough for me to take off the base with a Traxxas T-wrench. I may work on a Version 2 that uses screws instead of tape if you guys want, but have found screws just end up splitting the plastic. (Tape: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B001BHLRTY?psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00 )

Here's my standard 100x160mm sized PCB heated bed. Since I couldn't find a heated bed this size I designed my own. If you supply it with 12V it get's about 125 deg. C. I also made a manual temp. controller for it using a 555 timer ic, because my printer supply couldn't give more power to also supply the heated bed. The temp. is controlled by the 555 timer duty cycle, you can change the temperature turning the potentiometer. More info about it at http://jjshortcut.wordpress.com/2011/11/21/555-timer-controlled-heated-print-bed/

• Mill or etch or whatever it.
  • Solder the connectors/led to it.
  • Make (if necessary) the controller.
  • Print!
  • Don't burn your fingers!

comments.text: After some research, I've found that ShivInteger is apparently the creation of Matthew Plummer-Fernandez and Julien Deswaef.  They created a program that randomly mixes other people's work together and posts it to thingiverse.  All the authors whose work has been forcibly integraged get an email saying that their work has been remixed, only to find that the result was something far less useful or artistic than the individual parts.
comments.author: mccand

comments.text: yeah I thought about that after I made the comment - can't pack a virus into an obj file.  Right now this person has 158 designs posted in a few days...  I had something similar to the Just3DPrint thing happen to me with some company that had a fake store on the Sears Mall and was listing my products.  I am the only one selling my product (as I assemble them) so it was obviously a scam.  I had to be an incredible squeaky wheel to get Sears to take it down but they eventually did. Sometimes I wish a I had a few hacker tricks up my sleeve to get even with the con artists.

description.text:
This is the beginning of my automatic coil winder. the coil will to be fixed in the chuck.
The idea is to set a number of windings via Control interface, hit Start and wait until your coil is wound..
Next part will be a motor mount with light barrier for measuring the revoltions. Last but not least, even if i prefer plain C on AVRs, I'll put it on a Arduino Nano + SainSmart Keypad with 1602 LCD.. May take some days since i never programmed Arduinos before.. XD Haven't yet printed it but will do right after I got my printer working..

prusa i3 derivate

Doesn't Matter

Yes

0.2

60 %, since it doesn't need to be extremely strong

Notes: This is just what i configured in Slic3r, haven't yet printed it.
I use PLA.. tell me what works better for the claws ;)

I think I have completed the chuck so far. Next is a motor coupling with integrated wheel encoder for a light brake.
Electronics will work on basis of an arduino UNO and a sainsmart lcd keypad http://www.sainsmart.com/sainsmart-uno-1602-lcd-keypad-shield-v3-for-arduino-uno-mega-r3-atmel-avr.html I will do a new thing when it's completed (no matter if it works properly or not) , so hold on :-)

title: Rostock Max PWR & USB sockets
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Moving your Rostock Max from one place to another is not a breeze, because the power and USB cables come out at awkward places, and get stuck everywhere.
I fixed that !
  • First, find some parts :
    • a USB-B solder type connector (I recuperated mine from a scrap USB harddisk)
    • a standard USB cable with male type B connector on one end (never mind the other end)
    • an IEC male chassis plug (can be found on any scrap electrical equipment)
    • a standard IEC power cable (never mind the other end)
  • Then print this thing,
  • Glue in both connectors.
  • Cut the cables to an appropriate length, but not too short. Plenty of storage room in that area !
  • Solder on the cables.
  • Make an appropriate hole in the sideboard.
  • Screw or rivet the assembly to the sideboard.
  • Make a notch for your power cable to reach the power supply socket.
  • Connect everything up and put everything back in place.
    Enjoy !
    • This thing was made with Tinkercad.
    Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/lS1kYsXtI6r

SeeMeCNC

Rostock MAX BYOE

200 micron layer

Crosshatch 6mm

author: JeremyVS

description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/kTf6CpvMgwg

This is a sunken placeholder for the Replicape and its BeagleBone Black that fits on the inside of the top frame. I sunk the frame a bit from the edges because I wanted to be able to use ChrisParish's spool holder (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:454808) on top of the electronics. The original design was created by Elias Bakken, the creator of the Replicape, but his design would only be printable from an i3-sized bed (200x200mm), you couldn't print it in one piece on the standard KosselMini's 17cm diameter bed. This is my answer to the issue. Three parts instead of one. The three parts are held together by the screws holding down the BeagleBone.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

KosselMini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

40%

Assembly with the BBB & Replicape First off, make sure your BBB and Replipcape are NOT stacked. You won't be able to screw the M3s in place to hold the BBB into the frame. Take part 3 (the back part, where you have two holes facing the wall) and place it under the matching screw hole of parts 1 & 2. Place the BBB on top, and take an M3x12mm (or longer) screw for each of the back screw holes. Note that the BBB's holes are not aligned in a symmetrical rectangular pattern. Don't damage the BBB with slanted screws! Use M3 Nylock nuts to secure the BBB and holder assembly together from the underside (I suggest doing one, then a second on one side before inserting all screws). Once your whole frame and BBB are secured together, you can fit the Replicape to the BBB.

title: Kossel Mini Spool Holder Brackets: extended

description.text: This is an elongated bracket for ChrisParish's original spool holder. The reason is simple. I own a replicape that I wanted to fit at the top of the frame as well, with this holder http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1381574 However, the brackets as given originally, need to fit in the center of the top frame's sides. That was conflicting with the mount points for my replicape holder. So I realized that if the brackets were longer, I could actually half-turn the spool holder on the top of the frame so that the brackets would all be offset to one side. But they needed to be longer. This is the answer to that issue. Follow the original instructions and find the rest of the parts on ChrisParish's thing page: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:454808
